{"title_page": "FAAC Incorporated", "text_new": "'''FAAC Incorporated''' is an American immersive simulation training company. They began as a military contractor, providing flight and weapons simulation systems to the U.S. Air Force, but have since branched out into transit and transportation simulation, law enforcement, Fire/EMS, research, and human-interaction simulation. \n\nFAAC is notable for having developed the first bus transit training simulator (in 1999). In 2015 this simulator was named among the top 100 safety improvements of the last 150 years by the [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Public_Transportation_Association APTA].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apta.com/wp-content/uploads/Top100InnovationsFinal.pdf |title=APTA Top 100 Safety Innovations}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apta.com/research-technical-resources/safety-security/safety-management-resource-center/commemorating-100-years-of-safety-innovations/ |title=Commemorating 100 Years of Safety Innovations}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.masstransitmag.com/technology/press-release/12037764/faac-incorporated-faacs-bus-simulator-honored-as-one-of-countrystop-100-safety-innovations |title=FAAC's Simulator Named of Country's Top Safety Innovations}}</ref> FAAC also introduced the first full-mission CGI-based light rail train (LRT) simulator<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20040331005535/en/Arotechs-FAAC-Delivers-Full-Mission-Light-Rail |title=Arotech's FAAC Delivers First Full Mission Light Rail Simulator; Developed under $490,000 Contract with Houston Metropolitan Transit Authority}}</ref>, the first interactive full-cab immersive tractor-trailer truck simulators, first fully interactive simulators for Fire/EMS responders, and the first all-digital [[tactical engagement simulation]] systems for law enforcement.\n\n== History ==\nFAAC was founded in 1972. That same year, they delivered weapon simulations systems for the first simulation-based U.S. military air combat training systems, including the U.S. Air Force\u2019s [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Air_combat_maneuvering_instrumentation|Air Combat Manuevering Instrumentation] (ACMI) system, and the Navy\u2019s Air Combat Maneuvering Range (ACMR) and Tactical Air Crew Training System (TACTS). Soon after they were chosen to be the sole simulation software development provider for U.S. military integrated air defense systems ([https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integrated_Air_and_Missile_Defense IADS]) simulations, retaining this exclusive role through the 1990s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.faac.com/about/history/ |title=FAAC timeline}}</ref> They have since continued to provide systems and services to many branches of the military.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/arotech-training-simulation-division-faac-130500529.html |title=Arotech Training and Simulation Division\u2019s FAAC Incorporated Receives Army Simulator Maintenance Subcontract Valued at Up to $14M}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004 FAAC was acquired by [[Arotech Corporation]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arotech.com/about |title=Arotech Historical Timeline}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|}}\n\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.faac.com/ Official website]\n\n[[Category:Companies based in Washtenaw County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Defense companies of the United States]]\n", "text_old": "'''FAAC Incorporated''' is an American immersive simulation training company. They began as a military contractor, providing flight and weapons simulation systems to the U.S. Air Force, but have since branched out into transit and transportation simulation, law enforcement, Fire/EMS, research, and human-interaction simulation. \n\nFAAC is notable for having developed the first bus transit training simulator (in 1999). In 2015 this simulator was named among the top 100 safety improvements of the last 150 years by the [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Public_Transportation_Association APTA].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apta.com/wp-content/uploads/Top100InnovationsFinal.pdf |title=APTA Top 100 Safety Innovations}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apta.com/research-technical-resources/safety-security/safety-management-resource-center/commemorating-100-years-of-safety-innovations/ |title=Commemorating 100 Years of Safety Innovations}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.masstransitmag.com/technology/press-release/12037764/faac-incorporated-faacs-bus-simulator-honored-as-one-of-countrystop-100-safety-innovations |title=FAAC's Simulator Named of Country's Top Safety Innovations}}</ref> FAAC also introduced the first full-mission CGI-based light rail train (LRT) simulator{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20040331005535/en/Arotechs-FAAC-Delivers-Full-Mission-Light-Rail |title=Arotech's FAAC Delivers First Full Mission Light Rail Simulator; Developed under $490,000 Contract with Houston Metropolitan Transit Authority}}, the first interactive full-cab immersive tractor-trailer truck simulators, first fully interactive simulators for Fire/EMS responders, and the first all-digital [[tactical engagement simulation]] systems for law enforcement.\n\n== History ==\nFAAC was founded in 1972. That same year, they delivered weapon simulations systems for the first simulation-based U.S. military air combat training systems, including the U.S. Air Force\u2019s [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Air_combat_maneuvering_instrumentation|Air Combat Manuevering Instrumentation] (ACMI) system, and the Navy\u2019s Air Combat Maneuvering Range (ACMR) and Tactical Air Crew Training System (TACTS). Soon after they were chosen to be the sole simulation software development provider for U.S. military integrated air defense systems ([https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integrated_Air_and_Missile_Defense IADS]) simulations, retaining this exclusive role through the 1990s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.faac.com/about/history/ |title=FAAC timeline}}</ref> They have since continued to provide systems and services to many branches of the military.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/arotech-training-simulation-division-faac-130500529.html |title=Arotech Training and Simulation Division\u2019s FAAC Incorporated Receives Army Simulator Maintenance Subcontract Valued at Up to $14M}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004 FAAC was acquired by [[Arotech Corporation]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arotech.com/about |title=Arotech Historical Timeline}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|}}\n\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.faac.com/ Official website]\n\n[[Category:Companies based in Washtenaw County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Defense companies of the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Lonetone", "label": "safe", "comment": "missing <ref> tags", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FAAC_Incorporated"}
{"title_page": "Federal Correctional Institution, Otisville", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{short description|Medium-security federal prison for male inmates located near Otisville, New York}}\n{{Infobox prison\n| prison_name    = Federal Correctional Institution, Otisville\n| image          = FCI.OTISVILLE.jpg\n| image_size     = 300px\n| location       = [[Mount Hope, New York|Town of Mount Hope]], [[Orange County, New York|Orange County]],<br />near [[Otisville, New York]]\n| coordinates    = \n| status         = Operational\n| classification = Medium-security (with minimum-security prison camp)\n| population     = 825 (110 in prison camp)\n| opened         = 1977\n| closed         = \n| managed_by     = Federal Bureau of Prisons\n| warden         = J. Petrucci\n}}\n\nThe '''Federal Correctional Institution, Otisville (FCI Otisville)''' is a medium-security United States [[federal prison]] for male inmates located near [[Otisville, New York]]. It is operated by the [[Federal Bureau of Prisons]] (BOP), a division of the [[United States Department of Justice]]. It also includes a satellite prison camp for minimum-security male offenders.\n\nFCI Otisville is located in southeastern New York State, near the Pennsylvania and New Jersey borders, and {{convert|70|mi|km}} northwest of New York City. It is {{convert|1/4|mi|m}} from the [[Otisville Correctional Facility]], a medium-security state prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bop.gov/locations/institutions/otv/index.jsp |title=FCI Otisville |publisher=[[Federal Bureau of Prisons]] |date= |access-date=October 14, 2013 }}</ref> It is {{convert|22|mi|km}} from [[Monticello, New York]], {{Convert|28|mi|km}} from [[Kiryas Joel, New York|Kiryas Joel]], and {{convert|51|mi|km}} from [[Monsey, New York|Monsey]].<ref>{{cite news |last= Tannenbaum (Rabbi) |first=Gershon |url= http://5tjt.com/jews-in-prison/ |title= Jews in Prison |work= ''[[Five Towns Jewish Times]] |date= December 24, 2014 |access-date= October 24, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==Jewish Demographics==\n[[Aleph Institute]]'s prison outreach director, Rabbi Menachem Katz, stated that the BOP \"kind of unofficially designated it to meet the needs of Orthodox Jews\" due to the proximity to the [[Jews in New York City|Jewish population of New York City]].<ref name=Hymanjews>{{cite web |author= Hyman, Peter |url= http://nymag.com/news/intelligencer/46010/ |title= Medium-Security Seder |work= [[New York (magazine)|New York magazine]] |date= April 13, 2008 |access-date= October 24, 2017 }} \"Even so, it\u2019s a big deal among the unfree at the medium-security federal prison in Otisville,[...]\" (making it clear that this is the federal, not state, prison)</ref> Circa 2008 the warden of the prison stated 58 prisoners were Jewish, while Jewish Prisoner Services International chairperson Gary Friedman stated that about 120 prisoners were Jewish. FCI Otisville offers [[Passover Seder]]s, done in the prison cafeteria. Until other prisons began offering seders, prisoners at those institutions took buses to Otisville to partake in seders. Peter Hyman of ''[[New York (magazine)|New York magazine]]'' wrote \"Otisville still offers one of the more traditional Seders in the prison system.\"<ref name=Hymanjews/> Religious Jewish inmates request assignment to FCI Otisville for these reasons.<ref>{{cite web|author=Hawkins, Asher|url=https://www.forbes.com/2009/07/13/best-prisons-cushiest-madoff-personal-finance-lockups_slide/|title=In Pictures: America's 10 Cushiest Prisons|work=[[Forbes]]|date=July 13, 2009|access-date=October 24, 2017 |quote=It is often requested as a destination by observant Jewish cons, thanks to its full-time rabbi and availability of kosher food. }}</ref>\n\n==Notable incidents==\nOn August 11, 2009, former correction officer Hope Spinato (assigned to FCI Otisville) was sentenced to eight months in prison after pleading guilty to aiding and assisting an inmate serving a 17-year drug trafficking sentence, in briefly escaping the facility. An investigation by the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] found that Spinato became involved in a relationship with the inmate (not identified by the Bureau of Prisons) and drove the inmate between the facility and her home, on several occasions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Former Correctional Officer Sentenced to Eight Months in Federal Prison for Aiding and Assisting Escape|url=https://www.fbi.gov/newyork/press-releases/2009/nyfo081209.htm|publisher=Federal Bureau of Investigation|access-date=April 16, 2013|date=August 12, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n[[George Jung]], the basis for the 2001 film ''[[Blow (film)|Blow]]'', served time at FCI Otisville, but was later transferred to the [[Federal Correctional Institution, Fort Dix|Federal Correctional Institution]] in [[Fort Dix]], [[New Jersey]] before being released in 2017.\n\nIn the [[Spike Lee]] film ''[[25th Hour]]'', the protagonist Montgomery \"Monty\" Brogan spends his final day commiserating with friends and family before reporting to Otisville for a seven-year sentence.\n\nIn the opening of the 2010 film ''[[Wall Street: Money Never Sleeps]]'', the sequel to the 1987 film ''[[Wall Street (1987 film)|Wall Street]]'', [[Gordon Gekko]], played by [[Michael Douglas]], is released after serving an eight-year sentence for [[insider trading]] and [[securities fraud]] for his actions as a [[corporate raid]]er in the first movie. Although the scene was actually shot at [[Sing Sing]] state prison, Gekko mentions in the film that he served his sentence at FCI Otisville.\n\nIn ''[[The Mindy Project]]'', nurse Morgan refers to his time in Otisville for the theft of cars with his cousin.\n\nIn 2019, [[Mike \"The Situation\" Sorrentino]], who is famous from the MTV show [[Jersey Shore]], was sentenced to 8 months for tax fraud.\n\nIn ''[[Superman (1978 film)]]'' the henchman Otis(''[[Ned Beatty]]'') of ''[[Lex Luthor]]'' have placed his mark for his small city on Lex's map of the \"new\" west-coast, and called it Otisville. The reaction of Lex (''[[Gene Hackman]]'') are timeless!\n\n==Notable inmates (current and former)==\n===Current===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!width=11%|Inmate Name\n!width=9%|Register Number\n!width=23%|Status\n!width=57%|Details\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Darren Sharper|Darren Mallory Sharper]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 34209-034\n|Serving a sentence of 20 years\n|Sentenced to 20 years after pleading guilty to multiple rape and drug-related charges<ref>{{cite web|title=Sharper sentenced to 20 years in Louisiana rape case|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/2016/08/25/darren-sharper-sentenced-louisiana-rape-case/89371760/|work=USA Today|date=August 25, 2016|accessdate=August 26, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Billy McFarland (entrepreneur)|Billy McFarland]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 91186-054\n|Serving a sentence of 6 years\n|Sentenced to 6 years in October 2018 after pleading guilty to two counts of [[wire fraud]] amounting to more than $26 million that occurred during his promotion of the fraudulent [[Fyre Festival]] music festival.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Alvarez |first1=Edgar |title=Creator of doomed Fyre Festival gets six-year prison sentence |url=https://www.engadget.com/2018/10/11/billy-mcfarland-fyre-festival-sentenced-federal-prison/?yptr=yahoo|accessdate=October 11, 2018 |agency=Yahoo News |date=October 11, 2018 }}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Sholam Weiss]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 32610-054\n| Serving a sentence of 835 years, earliest possible release November 13, 2754.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Roberts|first1=Daniel|title=Orange is the New White-Collar|url=http://fortune.com/2014/07/07/orange-is-the-new-white-collar/|work=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]|access-date=October 5, 2015|date=July 7, 2014 }}</ref>\n| Convicted in 2000 of [[fraud]], [[Racket (crime)|racketeering]] and [[money laundering]] for stealing $450 million fro