/michael-cohen-otisville-prison-life\n|title=Here's a look at Michael Cohen's upcoming prison life\n|first1=Michael R.\n|last1=Sisak\n|first2=Jim\n|last2=Mustian\n|publisher=Boston.com / AP\n|date=May 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-46546238|title=Ex-Trump lawyer Cohen jailed for 36 months|date=December 12, 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=December 12, 2018|language=en-GB }}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Former===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!width=11%|Inmate Name\n!width=9%|Register Number\n!width=23%|Status\n!width=57%|Details\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Michele Sindona]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 00450-054\n| Originally sentenced to 25 years in June 1980 but [[extradited]] on September 25, 1984 to Italy to face [[murder]] charge\n| Sicilian banker and [[Propaganda Due]] boss with clear connections to the [[Mafia]]. Following the failure of the [[Franklin National Bank]], was sentenced on 65 counts<ref>\u2018Italian financier draws 25 years for bank fraud\u2019; ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', June 14, 1980, p. 12</ref> of [[fraud]], [[perjury]], false bank statements and [[misappropriation]] of $45,000,000 in bank funds.<ref>Firstman, Richard C.; \u2018He Lived As He Died: An Enigma\u2019; ''Newsday'', March 23, 1986, p. 03</ref> Was sentenced to life imprisonment in Italy in 1986 on charge of murdering lawyer [[Giorgio Ambrosoli]]<ref>\u2018Michele Sindona Gets Life Imprisonment In Murder Conspiracy\u2019; ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'', March 19, 1986, p. 1</ref> but committed suicide four days subsequently.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Sholom Rubashkin]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 10755-029\n|Released December 20, 2017; Originally sentenced to a 27-year sentence per presidential commutation.<ref>{{cite news|title=Trump commutes meatpacking executive's sentence, his first such use of the power |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/2017/12/20/dc217552-deef-11e7-bbd0-9dfb2e37492a_story.html|access-date=October 5, 2015|work= [[The Washington Post]] |date= December 20, 2017 }}</ref>\n| Former [[Chief executive officer|CEO]] of [[Agriprocessors]], once the largest [[Kashrut|kosher]] [[slaughterhouse]] in the United States; convicted of [[fraud]] for deceiving his lender, [[FirstMerit Corporation|First Bank Business Capital]], to receive loans totaling $26 million.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/11/13/us/13verdict.html|title=Slaughterhouse Manager Convicted in Fraud Case|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=October 16, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/22/us/22iowa.html|title=27-Year Sentence for Plant Manager|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=October 16, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/40535904/ |title=American Greed: The Slaughterhouse |work=CNBC |access-date=October 14, 2013 }}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Zvonko Bu\u0161i\u0107]]\u2020\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 03941-158\n| Released from custody in 2008 after serving 32 years.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pitt|first1=David E.|title=Hijacker OF '76 T.W.A. Flight Burrows Out of Federal Prison|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/04/18/nyregion/hijacker-of-76-twa-flight-burrows-out-of-federal-prison.html|access-date=October 5, 2015|work=The New York Times|date=April 18, 1987 }}</ref>\n| Member of a terrorist group seeking Croatian independence from [[Yugoslavia]]; planted a bomb at [[Grand Central Terminal]] in New York City that killed [[New York City Police Department|NYPD]] officer Brian Murray and [[Aircraft hijacking|hijacked]] [[TWA Flight 355]] in 1976; briefly escaped from FCI Otisville in 1987.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/nation/2008-07-19-terrorist_N.htm |title=Terrorist in NYC hijacking, bombing granted parole |website=Usatoday.Com |date=July 19, 2008 |access-date=October 14, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://dalje.com/en-croatia/us-concedes-amnesty-to-zvonko-busic-after-32-years/162527 |title=US Concedes Amnesty to Zvonko Busic After 32 Years - Current Events - Croatia |website=Dalje.com |date=July 8, 2008 |access-date=October 14, 2013  |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014180631/http://dalje.com/en-croatia/us-concedes-amnesty-to-zvonko-busic-after-32-years/162527 |archive-date=October 14, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Michael Sorrentino|Michael \"The Situation\" Sorrentino]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 66910-050\n|Served a sentence of 8 months; released September 2019.\n|Sentenced to 8 months in prison after pleading guilty to tax fraud in October 2018<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tmz.com/2019/01/15/mike-the-situation-surrenders-prison-sentence-tax-evasion/ |title=Mike 'The Situation' Sorrentino Officially Booked into Prison |work=TMZ |date=January 15, 2019 |access-date=January 15, 2019 }}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Walter Forbes]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 23905-050\n| Served a 12-year sentence; Released in 2018.<ref name=\"associated2007\">{{cite news|title=Ex-Cendant Chairman Sentenced for Fraud|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/18/business/18cendant.html?ref=walteraforbes&_r=0|access-date=June 21, 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|date=January 18, 2007 }}</ref>\n| Former Chairman of [[Cendant|Cendant Corporation]] convicted in 2007 of conspiracy to commit [[securities fraud]] and making false statements for masterminding the largest accounting fraud of the 1990s; Forbes was also ordered to pay $3.275 billion in [[restitution]].<ref name=\"associated2007\"/>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Kenneth I. Starr]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 63552-054\n| Served a 7-year sentence;  released in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=Corrupt Ex-Pol Now Doing Time In New York|url=http://queens-politics.com/2014/03/corrupt-ex-pol-now-doing-time-in-new-york-brian/|website=Queens Politics|access-date=September 18, 2015|date=March 26, 2014 }}</ref>\n| Former financial adviser for [[Al Pacino]], [[Martin Scorsese]] and [[Sylvester Stallone]]; pleaded guilty in 2010 to [[fraud]] and [[money laundering]] for diverting $33 million of his clients\u2019 money to pay for personal expenses.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/09/11/business/11fraud.html|title=Guilty Plea in Fraud by Adviser to Stars|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=October 16, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/03/03/ken-starr-hollywoods-mado_n_830918.html |title=Ken Starr, Hollywood's Madoff, Gets Sentenced |website=Huffingtonpost.com |date=March 3, 2011 |access-date=October 14, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/45554694 |title=American Greed: Celebrity Scam Artist |work=CNBC |date= |access-date=October 14, 2013 }}</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal bar|United States|Politics|New York (state)|Law}}\n* [[List of United States federal prisons]]\n* [[Federal Bureau of Prisons]]\n* [[Incarceration in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.bop.gov/locations/institutions/otv/ Federal Bureau of Prisons: FCI Otisville]\n \n{{coord|41|29|47|N|74|31|38|W|scale:10000|display=title}}\n{{Federal Bureau of Prisons}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings of the United States government in New York]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Orange County, New York]]\n[[Category:Federal Correctional Institutions in the United States]]\n[[Category:Economy of Orange County, New York]]\n[[Category:Prisons in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:1977 establishments in New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{short description|Medium-security federal prison for male inmates located near Otisville, New York}}\n{{Infobox prison\n| prison_name    = Federal Correctional Institution, Otisville\n| image          = FCI.OTISVILLE.jpg\n| image_size     = 300px\n| location       = [[Mount Hope, New York|Town of Mount Hope]], [[Orange County, New York|Orange County]],<br />near [[Otisville, New York]]\n| coordinates    = \n| status         = Operational\n| classification = Medium-security (with minimum-security prison camp)\n| population     = 825 (110 in prison camp)\n| opened         = 1977\n| closed         = \n| managed_by     = Federal Bureau of Prisons\n| warden         = J. Petrucci\n}}\n\nThe '''Federal Correctional Institution, Otisville (FCI Otisville)''' is a medium-security United States [[federal prison]] for male inmates located near [[Otisville, New York]]. It is operated by the [[Federal Bureau of Prisons]] (BOP), a division of the [[United States Department of Justice]]. It also includes a satellite prison camp for minimum-security male offenders.\n\nFCI Otisville is located in southeastern New York State, near the Pennsylvania and New Jersey borders, and {{convert|70|mi|km}} northwest of New York City. It is {{convert|1/4|mi|m}} from the [[Otisville Correctional Facility]], a medium-security state prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bop.gov/locations/institutions/otv/index.jsp |title=FCI Otisville |publisher=[[Federal Bureau of Prisons]] |date= |access-date=October 14, 2013 }}</ref> It is {{convert|22|mi|km}} from [[Monticello, New York]], {{Convert|28|mi|km}} from [[Kiryas Joel, New York|Kiryas Joel]], and {{convert|51|mi|km}} from [[Monsey, New York|Monsey]].<ref>{{cite news |last= Tannenbaum (Rabbi) |first=Gershon |url= http://5tjt.com/jews-in-prison/ |title= Jews in Prison |work= ''[[Five Towns Jewish Times]] |date= December 24, 2014 |access-date= October 24, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==Jewish Demographics==\n[[Aleph Institute]]'s prison outreach director, Rabbi Menachem Katz, stated that the BOP \"kind of unofficially designated it to meet the needs of Orthodox Jews\" due to the proximity to the [[Jews in New York City|Jewish population of New York City]].<ref name=Hymanjews>{{cite web |author= Hyman, Peter |url= http://nymag.com/news/intelligencer/46010/ |title= Medium-Security Seder |work= [[New York (magazine)|New York magazine]] |date= April 13, 2008 |access-date= October 24, 2017 }} \"Even so, it\u2019s a big deal among the unfree at the medium-security federal prison in Otisville,[...]\" (making it clear that this is the federal, not state, prison)</ref> Circa 2008 the warden of the prison stated 58 prisoners were Jewish, while Jewish Prisoner Services International chairperson Gary Friedman stated that about 120 prisoners were Jewish. FCI Otisville offers [[Passover Seder]]s, done in the prison cafeteria. Until other prisons began offering seders, prisoners at those institutions took buses to Otisville to partake in seders. Peter Hyman of ''[[New York (magazine)|New York magazine]]'' wrote \"Otisville still offers one of the more traditional Seders in the prison system.\"<ref name=Hymanjews/> Religious Jewish inmates request assignment to FCI Otisville for these reasons.<ref>{{cite web|author=Hawkins, Asher|url=https://www.forbes.com/2009/07/13/best-prisons-cushiest-madoff-personal-finance-lockups_slide/|title=In Pictures: America's 10 Cushiest Prisons|work=[[Forbes]]|date=July 13, 2009|access-date=October 24, 2017 |quote=It is often requested as a destination by observant Jewish cons, thanks to its full-time rabbi and availability of kosher food. }}</ref>\n\n==Notable incidents==\nOn August 11, 2009, former correction officer Hope Spinato (assigned to FCI Otisville) was sentenced to eight months in prison after pleading guilty to aiding and assisting an inmate serving a 17-year drug trafficking sentence, in briefly escaping the facility. An investigation by the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] found that Spinato became involved in a relationship with the inmate (not identified by the Bureau of Prisons) and drove the inmate between the facility and his home, on several occasions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Former Correctional Officer Sentenced to Eight Months in Federal Prison for Aiding and Assisting Escape|url=https://www.fbi.gov/newyork/press-releases/2009/nyfo081209.htm|publisher=Federal Bureau of Investigation|access-date=April 16, 2013|date=August 12, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n[[George Jung]], the basis for the 2001 film ''[[Blow (film)|Blow]]'', served time at FCI Otisville, but was later transferred to the [[Federal Correctional Institution, Fort Dix|Federal Correctional Institution]] in [[Fort Dix]], [[New Jersey]] before being released in 2017.\n\nIn the [[Spike Lee]] film ''[[25th Hour]]'', the protagonist Montgomery \"Monty\" Brogan spends his final day commiserating with friends and family before reporting to Otisville for a seven-year sentence.\n\nIn the opening of the 2010 film ''[[Wall Street: Money Never Sleeps]]'', the sequel to the 1987 film ''[[Wall Street (1987 film)|Wall Street]]'', [[Gordon Gekko]], played by [[Michael Douglas]], is released after serving an eight-year sentence for [[insider trading]] and [[securities fraud]] for his actions as a [[corporate raid]]er in the first movie. Although the scene was actually shot at [[Sing Sing]] state prison, Gekko mentions in the film that he served his sentence at FCI Otisville.\n\nIn ''[[The Mindy Project]]'', nurse Morgan refers to his time in Otisville for the theft of cars with his cousin.\n\nIn 2019, [[Mike \"The Situation\" Sorrentino]], who is famous from the MTV show [[Jersey Shore]], was sentenced to 8 months for tax fraud.\n\nIn ''[[Superman (1978 film)]]'' the henchman Otis(''[[Ned Beatty]]'') of ''[[Lex Luthor]]'' have placed his mark for his small city on Lex's map of the \"new\" west-coast, and called it Otisville. The reaction of Lex (''[[Gene Hackman]]'') are timeless!\n\n==Notable inmates (current and former)==\n===Current===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!width=11%|Inmate Name\n!width=9%|Register Number\n!width=23%|Status\n!width=57%|Details\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Darren Sharper|Darren Mallory Sharper]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 34209-034\n|Serving a sentence of 20 years\n|Sentenced to 20 years after pleading guilty to multiple rape and drug-related charges<ref>{{cite web|title=Sharper sentenced to 20 years in Louisiana rape case|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/2016/08/25/darren-sharper-sentenced-louisiana-rape-case/89371760/|work=USA Today|date=August 25, 2016|accessdate=August 26, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Billy McFarland (entrepreneur)|Billy McFarland]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 91186-054\n|Serving a sentence of 6 years\n|Sentenced to 6 years in October 2018 after pleading guilty to two counts of [[wire fraud]] amounting to more than $26 million that occurred during his promotion of the fraudulent [[Fyre Festival]] music festival.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Alvarez |first1=Edgar |title=Creator of doomed Fyre Festival gets six-year prison sentence |url=https://www.engadget.com/2018/10/11/billy-mcfarland-fyre-festival-sentenced-federal-prison/?yptr=yahoo|accessdate=October 11, 2018 |agency=Yahoo News |date=October 11, 2018 }}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Sholam Weiss]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 32610-054\n| Serving a sentence of 835 years, earliest possible release November 13, 2754.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Roberts|first1=Daniel|title=Orange is the New White-Collar|url=http://fortune.com/2014/07/07/orange-is-the-new-white-collar/|work=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]|access-date=October 5, 2015|date=July 7, 2014 }}</ref>\n| Convicted in 2000 of [[fraud]], [[Racket (crime)|racketeering]] and [[money laundering]] for stealing $450 million from the now-defunct Heritage Life Insurance Corporation between 1990 and 1998.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2000-02-16/news/0002150484_1_fawsett-weiss-heritage-life-insurance |title=Insurance Crooks To Serve Life - Plus - tribunedigital-orlandosentinel |work=[[Orlando Sentinel]] |date=February 16, 2000 |access-date=October 25, 2015 }}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Dean Skelos]]\n| s